2.c) Let's create a function to plot the pie-charts¶

In [17]:
# creating a function which takes dataframe as parameter.

def pie_chart(dataframe):
    cat_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes('object').columns
    cat_columns = [col for col in cat_columns]
    cat_columns.remove('customerID')
    plt.figure(figsize = (15,15))
    for i, column in enumerate(cat_columns):
        plt.subplot(4,4,i+1)
        plt.title(f"pie_chart for '{column}'")
        values = churn[column].value_counts()
        plt.pie(values, labels = values.index, autopct = '%1.1f%%')
In [18]:

churn['gender'] = churn['gender'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'Male' else 1)
churn['Partner'] = churn['Partner'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'No' else 1)
churn['Dependents'] = churn['Dependents'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'No' else 1)
churn['PhoneService'] = churn['PhoneService'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'No' else 1)
churn['MultipleLines'] = churn['MultipleLines'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Yes' else 0)
churn['InternetService'] = churn['InternetService'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'No' else(1 if x == 'Fiber optic' else 2))
churn['OnlineSecurity'] = churn['OnlineSecurity'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Yes' else 0)
churn['OnlineBackup'] = churn['OnlineBackup'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Yes' else 0)
churn['DeviceProtection'] = churn['DeviceProtection'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Yes' else 0)
churn['TechSupport'] = churn['TechSupport'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Yes' else 0)
churn['StreamingTV'] = churn['StreamingTV'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Yes' else 0)
churn['StreamingMovies'] = churn['StreamingMovies'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Yes' else 0)
churn['Contract'] = churn['Contract'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'Month-to-month' else (1 if x == 'One year' else 2))
churn['PaperlessBilling'] = churn['PaperlessBilling'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Yes' else 0)
churn['Churn'] = churn['Churn'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Yes' else 0)

MODEL BUILDING¶

3.a) Let's bulid a Decision Tree¶

  • Let's create a function to print all the metrics of the model.
In [29]:
from sklearn.metrics import *
# Function to print all the metrics of the model.
def metrics_function(y_actual, y_pred):
    Accuracy_Score  = accuracy_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    Precision_Score = precision_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    Recall_Score =  recall_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    F1_Score = f1_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    AUC_Score = roc_auc_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    return Accuracy_Score, Precision_Score, Recall_Score, F1_Score, AUC_Score
In [30]:
# Function for confusion_matrix.
def cf_matrix(y_actual, y_pred):
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_actual, y_pred)
    cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = ['Actual-No', 'Actual-yes'], columns = ['Pred-No', 'Pred-Yes'])
    plt.figure(figsize = (3,2))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, cbar = False, fmt = 'g')
    plt.show()

3.b) Let's tune the Hyper_Parameters of the DecisionTreeClassifier using GridSearchCV¶

In [37]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

parameters = {'min_samples_leaf':[100,200,300],
             'max_depth':[1,3,5,7],
              'criterion':['gini', 'entropy'],
              'max_features':[0.2,0.3,0.4,0.5],
              'min_samples_split':[100,200,300,400,500]
             }
tree_tuning = GridSearchCV(DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = 1), param_grid = parameters, cv = 5, scoring = make_scorer(recall_score))
In [38]:
start = time.time()
tree_tuning = tree_tuning.fit(X_train, y_train)
end = time.time()
execusion_time = end - start
In [39]:

Observations¶

  • In Base Decision tree classifier the average scores of the training data is 99%. But in testing data the scores are very low..Model is predicting only 50% of the True Positives.
  • Base model is overfitting as it is performing well on the training data but not on the testing data.
  • After tuning the Hyperparameters using Grid search cv train Accuracy decreased to 77% and test Accuracy improved by 3%.
  • Precision score and Recall scores are also decreased to 61% and 37% in training data.
  • Recall score for testing data has also decreased.
  • So, even after tuning the hyper parameters, the model is not much performing on both training and testing data.

3.I) (1)Let's compare all the trained models¶

  • (i) Base decision tree was overfitted. It is performing well on the training data but not on the testing data.
  • (ii) After tuning the base tree model Train scores are decreased and test accuracy increased but Recall score has decreased.
  • (iii) Random forest model also overfitted, But scores on testing data are high comparing with base Decision Tree model.
  • (iv) In tuned Random Forest model, due to class_weight's ratio Recall scores of the testing data has increased to 66%.
  • (v) Base Ada boost is performing well on both training and testing data.
  • (vi) There is no such difference b/w base and tuned Ada boosting model.
  • (vii) In both Gradient boost classifiers test score uus 80% but Recall scores are 50% and 54%.

2) Best Model¶

  • According to the Problem statement, our goal is to predict the customers who are going to churn.
  • Tuned Random Forest model is predicting more True Positives comparing with the other models.
  • Accuracy scores of traing and testing data are also close to each other.
  • None of the model is giving 63% of Recall score except Randomforest model.
  • According to the Accuracy score AdaBoost and GradientBoost models are performing well.

3) Why this model is performing well?¶

  • While tuning the Hyper parameters of the Random Forest model the class_weights ratio set to 0.4:0.6 ratio.
  • So, the model is more effective in predicting the class-'Yes'.

4) Conclusion¶

  • Here our objective is to find maximum no of counts that who are going to churn.
  • So, After tuning random forest classifier is giving good Recall score(63%) comparing with other models.
  • Therefore, tuned Random forest classifier is predicting maximum counts of the customers who are going to churn.
